{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141103001448|632212910","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Paul_Tonko","to":"Paul Tonko"}],"pages":{"6984664":{"pageid":6984664,"ns":0,"title":"Paul Tonko","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-18T04:15:18Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Paul Tonko\n| image name      = Paultonko.jpg\n| imagesize       = 220px\n| caption         =\n| state1          = New York\n| district1       = [[New York's 20th congressional district|20th]]\n| term_start1     = January 3, 2013\n| predecessor1    = [[Chris Gibson (New York politician)|Chris Gibson]]\n| successor1      = \n| state2          = New York\n| district2       = [[New York's 21st congressional district|21st]]\n| term_start2     = January 3, 2009\n| term_end2       = January 3, 2013\n| predecessor2    = [[Michael R. McNulty]]\n| successor2      = [[Bill Owens (congressman)|Bill Owens]]\n| state3          = New York\n| state_assembly3 = New York\n| district3       = 105th\n| term_start3     = April 1983\n| term_end3       = June 2007\n| predecessor3    = [[Gail Shaffer]]\n| successor3      = [[George Amedore]]\n| party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1949|6|18}}\n| birth_place     = [[Amsterdam (city), New York|Amsterdam, New York]]\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| alma_mater      = [[Clarkson University]]\n| profession      = Engineer\n| spouse          = Single\n| residence       = [[Amsterdam, New York]]\n| religion        = Roman Catholic\n| website         = [http://www.paultonko.com/ Congressional Campaign Website]\n}}\n\n'''Paul David Tonko''' (born June 18, 1949) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|New York|20}}, a post he has held since 2009. He is a member of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]].  The district, numbered as the 21st for his first two terms, is located in the heart of the [[Capital District]] and includes [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[Schenectady]] and [[Troy, New York|Troy]]. Tonko previously represented the 105th District in the [[New York Assembly]] from 1983 to 2007.\n\nTonko was president and CEO of the [[New York State Energy Research and Development Authority]], from 2007 until his resignation on April 25, 2008,<ref>{{cite web| title = Tonko resigns from NYSERDA| publisher = Albany Business Review| date = 28 April 2008| url = http://www.bizjournals.com/albany/stories/2008/04/28/daily2.html| accessdate = 19 June 2014}}</ref> in which he declared his candidacy for Congress shortly after.\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nTonko is a lifelong resident of [[Amsterdam (city), New York|Amsterdam, New York]], near Schenectady. He holds a degree in [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical]] and [[Industrial Engineering]] from [[Clarkson University]]. He is of Polish descent.<ref>http://tonko.house.gov/press-releases/congressman-paul-tonko-speaks-on-polish-tragedy/</ref>\n\nTonko was a member, and subsequently Chair, of the [[Montgomery County, New York|Montgomery County Board of Supervisors]]. He also worked for a brief time as an engineer for the New York State Department of Public Service.\n\n==New York Assembly (1983-2007)==\nHe represented the 105th District, which comprises Amsterdam, [[Rotterdam (town), New York|Rotterdam]], [[Princetown, New York|Princetown]], [[Mohawk, Montgomery County, New York|Mohawk]], [[Glen, New York|Glen]] and part of [[Schenectady]].<ref name=\"book-redbook\">{{cite book |editor-first= |editor-last= |title=New York Red Book |url=http://www.nylp.com/online_cat/body.html#3 |edition=2007\u201308 |publisher=New York Legal Publishing Corp. |location=Albany, N.Y. |issn=0196-4623 |page=965}}</ref>\n\n===Elections===\nIncumbent Democratic Assemblywoman [[Gail Shaffer]] resigned from her seat to become the [[New York Secretary of State]].<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=75820 Our Campaigns - Candidate - Gail S. Shaffer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Tonko ran for the seat in an April 1983 special election against Republican Eugene Hallock, and won with 54% of the vote.<ref name=\"book-redbook\" /><ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=171019 Our Campaigns - NY Assembly 105 Special Race - Apr 12, 1983<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He won re-election 15 more times. He never won re-election with less than 62% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=47039 Our Campaigns - Candidate - Paul D. Tonko<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nTonko was also the major advocate of \"Timothy's Law\" to require health insurers to cover mental illness.<ref name=\"pr-bruno1\">{{cite press release | title = Senate Passes \"Timothy's Law\" to Provide Mental Health Parity | publisher=The Senate Republican Majority | date = September 15, 2006 | url = http://www.senate.state.ny.us/pressreleases.nsf/6d7ac8927bea79d085256b76006cc004/8fd916340beb347c852571ea00738456?OpenDocument | accessdate =January 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAssemblyman Tonko was a chief sponsor of the [[Northeast Dairy Compact]],<ref name=\"sdg-lamendola1\">{{cite news | first = Michael | last = Lamendola | title = Tonko wins to succeed McNulty | url = http://www.dailygazette.com/news/2008/nov/05/1105_tonko/ | work=The Daily Gazette | location = [[Schenectady, New York]] | date = November 5, 2008 | accessdate =January 15, 2009 }}</ref> the Chairman of the Legislative Commission on Rural Resources,<ref name=\"ods-anon1\">{{cite news | title = Tonko speaking at SUNY Cobleskill | url = http://old.thedailystar.com/news/stories/2007/05/18/cobygrad12.html | work=The Daily Star | location = [[Oneonta, New York]] | date = May 18, 2007 | accessdate =January 15, 2009 }}</ref> and was appointed by Speaker [[Sheldon Silver]] to serve as Commissioner for the [[Mohawk Valley]] Heritage Corridor Commission.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}\n\nTonko vacated his seat on June 29, 2007 to become the President and CEO of the New York State Energy Research and Development Authority, otherwise known as NYSERDA.\n\n===Committee assignments===\nWhile in the Assembly, Tonko served as the Chairman of the [[New York energy law|Energy Committee]], a position he held from 1992 until retirement. Tonko was also a member of standing committees on Agriculture, Transportation and Education, where he was the original sponsor and a chief proponent of the College Tuition Savings Program that was signed into law in 1997.<ref name=\"nyt-eaton1\">{{cite news | first = Leslie | last = Eaton | title = New Yorkers Rush to Invest In College Plan | url = http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03E5D81F3BF935A35751C1A96E958260&sec=&spon=&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink | work=New York Times | location = New York, New York | date = December 6, 1998 | accessdate =January 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==CEO of NYSERDA (2007-2008)==\n{{see also|NYSERDA|Energy law|New York energy law}}\n\nTonko was President and CEO of [http://www.nyserda.ny.gov/ NYSERDA] (New York State Energy Research and Development Authority) from 2007 to 2008, when he resigned to run for U.S. Representative.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2008-present)==\n\n===Elections===\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2008#District 21}}\nTonko entered the 2008 Democratic Primary for New York State's 21st Congressional District after 10-term incumbent [[Michael McNulty]] (with whom he served in the State Assembly from 1983 to 1989) decided to retire.<ref>[http://www.elections.ny.gov:8080/reports/rwservlet?cmdkey=candidate_32_statewide_cgs New York State Board of Elections website list of candidates].  Retrieved September 11, 2008.</ref> Despite having less money than both his main rivals, Tonko won the primary on September 9, 2008 with a plurality of 40% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=406086 Our Campaigns - NY District 21 - D Primary Race - Sep 09, 2008<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=\"Its Tonko\">Lauren Stanforth, \"It's Tonko in 21st: Democrat will face Buhrmaster,\" September 10, 2008, found at\n[http://www.timesunion.com/AspStories/story.asp?storyID=719257&category=REGION Times Union website]</ref> He ran against Republican James Buhrmaster, a [[Schenectady County, New York|Schenectady County]] legislator, in the general election.<ref name=\"Its Tonko\" />\n\nDemocrats outnumber Republicans in registration in the district by a count of 174,054 to 119,493, with 101,219 not enrolled in any party and a total of 428,655 Voters Registered as of March 1, 2008. As such, it was generally believed Tonko had assured himself of a seat in Congress with his victory in the primary.\n\nOn November 4, 2008, Tonko won in a landslide, with over 60% of the total vote.<ref name=win>Standforth, Lauren, and Carol Demare, \"Tonko cruises to win in 21st Congressional District: Democrat goes to D.C. with handy win over Buhrmaster\", November 5, 2008, found at [http://timesunion.com/AspStories/story.asp?storyID=736413 Election coverage]. Retrieved November 5, 2008.</ref> \"Tonko's name recognition ... accomplishment in the Legislature, such as the passage of mental health parity legislation, and his record\" contributed to his win.<ref name=win /> According to preliminary figures the day after the election, he beat Burhmaster by 105,313 to 57,086, with Philip Steck, a minor party candidate, receiving 5,025 votes.<ref name=win />\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2010#District 21}}\nIn 2010, Tonko ran for re-election on the Democratic, Working Families and Independence Party lines.  He was challenged by Republican and Conservative Party nominee Ted Danz, a former United States Navy Reservist and small business owner in the cooling and heating business.  ''[[Congressional Quarterly]]'' rated the race as \"Safe\" for the incumbent party to keep the seat.<ref>[http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=district-2010-NY-21 Race ranking and details] from [[Congressional Quarterly|CQ Politics]].  Accessed December 20, 2010.</ref>  Tonko raised almost $980,000, and spent almost $780,000 on his campaign; Danz raised about $44,000 and spent about $42,000 for his own campaign.<ref>[http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?id=NY21&cycle=2010 Campaign contributions] from [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]].  Accessed December 20, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"Times profile\">[http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/house/new-york/21 Race profile] at ''[[The New York Times]]''.  Accessed December 20, 2010.</ref>  The seat was rated by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as being \"Solid Democratic\" with \"99.8 %\" to \"100 % chance\" that Tonko would win the seat.<ref name=\"Times profile\" />  The major issues in the 2010 race were Tonko's \"yes\" votes for the Health Care Bill, the Stimulus Package ([[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|ARRA]]), and the Energy Bill.<ref name=\"Times profile\" />  The ''[[Albany Times Union]]'' endorsed Tonko in that race, citing \"a way of thinking and speaking like the engineer that he once was\" and his support of the economic stimulus bill and health care bills.<ref>Editorial, \"Paul Tonko for Congress,\"\n''[[Albany Times Union]]'' , October 27, 2010.  Found at [http://www.timesunion.com/opinion/article/Paul-Tonko-for-Congress-725101.php Times Union.com]. Accessed December 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nTonko won the general election on November 2, 2010, by a vote of 124,889 to 85,752.<ref>[http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010Congress.pdf New York State Board of elections official returns for November 2, 2010]. Accessed December 20, 2010.</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2012#District 20}}\nTonko was challenged by Republican Bob Dieterich, senior vice president at First National Bank of Scotia. Former Tonko opponent Jim Buhrmaster cited Albany, particularly the city, as the biggest challenge for a Republican contender. He added, however: \u201cPeople are voting more independently, and they\u2019re not registering Republican or Democratic.\u201d<ref name=\"2012 Challenger\">{{cite news|title=Paul Tonko gains a challenger|url=http://blog.timesunion.com/capitol/archives/119326/paul-tonko-gains-a-challenger/|newspaper=Times Union|date=6 March 2012}}</ref> Tonko won re-election with about 62% of the vote.\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2014#District20}}\nTonko was challenged by Jim Fischer in the November 2014 election. He won his fourth term with 59% of the vote.<ref>http://ballotpedia.org/Paul_Tonko#2014</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nTonko was one of the 19 most liberal house members, according to the ''[[National Journal]]'', for 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nationaljournal.com/pictures-video/most-liberal-house-members-pictures-20120223 | work=National Journal|title=Most Liberal House Members -- PICTURES |date=February 23, 2012|accessdate=March 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen he entered Congress, Tonko said he wanted to focus on the issue he said he knows best \u2013 energy policy.<ref name=Almanac>{{cite web|title=Rep. Paul Tonko (D)|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/paul-tonko-ny/|publisher=The National Journal}}</ref> He sponsored a bill to get $800 million research program in [[wind energy]] technologies, which would benefit [[GE Energy|GE]] in his district. He also wanted to create a research program to improve the efficiency of [[gas turbines]] used in power generation systems that convert heat into energy. In 2010, Tonko got a provision in a House-passed bill, following the [[BP oil spill|BP disaster in the Gulf of Mexico]], to prevent future spills and help small businesses in spill research. In 2011, he sponsored an amendment seeking to protect the [[Environmental Protection Agency]]\u2019s authority to regulate carbon emissions.<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/person/paul-tonko-ny/ ]{{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is strongly against expanding the [[Bush-era tax cuts]] for high-income earners. Among other key votes, he voted for the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]],<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll638.xml</ref> [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]],<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll165.xml</ref> [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]],<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll477.xml</ref> and [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]].<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll046.xml</ref> He voted against the Republicans' budget.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/112/house/1/votes/277/ |title=GOP 2012 Budget Plan | work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nTonko has contributed blog posts to the [[Huffington Post]], with many sharply criticizing the Republican Party, including their \"budget hypocrisy\" and the threat they pose to Social Security. He praised the 2011 State of the Union address, saying: \u201cthe President set out a bold agenda for our nation, an agenda that will focus on growing our economy, growing jobs, and growing opportunity for the middle class\u201d.<ref name=\"Response 2011\">{{cite news|last=Tonko|first=Paul|title=State of the Union Response|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rep-paul-tonko/state-of-the-union-respon_b_814981.html|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=January 27, 2011}}</ref> On numerous occasions, he has also warned of the threat that would allegedly be posed by the healthcare repeal to small businesses, to young people, and to seniors.<ref name=\"Tonko HuffPost\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Paul Tonko|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rep-paul-tonko|publisher=The Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nTonko has also worked to raise awareness about the region's waterways, chiefly the Hudson and Mowhawk rivers, and the effects of recent flooding following Hurricane Irene. Seeking a comprehensive flood mitigation and economic development strategy, Tonko introduced the Hudson-Mohawk Basin Act in 2012.<ref name=\"Basin Bill Times Union\">{{cite news|url= http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Tonko-bill-casts-wide-river-net-3690753.php#page-1|title=Tonko bill casts wide river net|last=LeBrun|first=Fred|work=timesunion.com}}</ref>\n\nHe was actively involved in floor debates against the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]].\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n**[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Subcommittee on Environment and Economy]], Ranking Member\n**[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n**[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*[[Addiction, Treatment and Recovery Caucus|Congressional Addiction, Treatment and Recovery Caucus]]\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n*Heritage Corridor Caucus\n*[[Congressional Biomass Caucus]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Energy law]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://tonko.house.gov/ Congressman Paul D. Tonko] official U.S. House site\n*[http://paultonko.com/ Paul Tonko for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Paul_D._Tonko_%5BD-20%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = T000469 | ballot = Paul_Tonko | nndb = 653/000180113 | votesmart = 4403 | govtrack = 412319 | opencong = 412319 | rollcall = 29506 | politifact = | fec = H8NY21203 | opensecrets = N00030196 | assets = paul-tonko | legistorm = 969/Rep_Paul_Tonko.html | followthemoney = 739 | ontheissues = NY/Paul_Tonko.htm | congress = paul-tonko/1942 | worldcat = lccn-n97-74743 | c-span = paultonko | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQA3w8MAP }}\n*[http://opensecrets.org/races/summary.asp?ID=NY21&Cycle=2008 Campaign contributions in 2008] at [[OpenSecrets.org]]\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rep-paul-tonko/ Blog archive] at ''[[The Huffington Post]]''\n*[http://www.neny.org/ContentManager/index.cfm?Step=Display&ContentID=40 Biography from ''New Energy New York'']\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{succession box|title=[[New York State Assembly|New York State Assembly, 105th District]]|before=[[Gail Schaffer|Gail Shaffer]]|years=1983\u20132007|after=[[George Amedore]] }}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=New York|\n  district=21 |\n  before=[[Michael R. McNulty]] |\n  after=[[Bill Owens (congressman)|Bill Owens]] |\n  start=2009 |\n  end=2013}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=New York|\n  district=20 |\n  before=[[Chris Gibson (New York politician)|Chris Gibson]] |\n  start=2013}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Glenn Thompson (politician)|Glenn Thompson]]<br><small>R-[[Pennsylvania]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=258th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Quigley (politician)|Michael Quigley]]<br><small>D-[[Illinois]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{NY-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              =Tonko, Paul\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIP